WEBVTT

00:07.448 --> 00:13.551
♪♪

00:13.655 --> 00:19.793
♪♪

00:19.896 --> 00:23.172
[ Fly buzzing ]

00:23.275 --> 00:26.551
[ Elevator humming ]

00:26.655 --> 00:27.758
[ Elevator bell dings ]

00:27.862 --> 00:30.034
I can't fucking believe
we have to fucking work

00:30.137 --> 00:32.206
on fucking Labor Day.

00:32.310 --> 00:33.413
It's like everyone died.

00:33.517 --> 00:35.275
Except worse,
because they didn't.

00:35.379 --> 00:38.758
At least there are fewer
distractions here than at home.

00:38.862 --> 00:41.068
I can't believe Kate and John
gave us an assignment

00:41.172 --> 00:42.620
due the day
after Labor Day.

00:42.724 --> 00:45.379
This is corporate fascism,
and we are big-time victims.

00:45.482 --> 00:48.551
In fairness, they did give us
the assignment two months ago.

00:48.655 --> 00:50.448
Oh, I'm sorry.
What were we supposed to do?

00:50.551 --> 00:53.172
Evenly spread out the work
over the course of a few weeks?

00:53.275 --> 00:56.620
You're right. That's crazy.
We are big-timevictims.

00:56.724 --> 00:59.586
Thank you! [ Scoffs ]

00:59.689 --> 01:05.655
♪♪

01:05.758 --> 01:11.620
♪♪

01:11.724 --> 01:18.172
♪♪

01:22.724 --> 01:24.620
[ Ding! ]

01:24.724 --> 01:25.827
[ Singsong voice ]
It's beginning to look

01:25.931 --> 01:27.241
a lot like Labor Day.

01:27.344 --> 01:28.413
Now that we have
every light source

01:28.517 --> 01:29.896
in the building running
through one outlet,

01:30.000 --> 01:31.241
let's write this speech
about reducing

01:31.344 --> 01:32.827
Hampton DeVille's
carbon footprint.

01:32.931 --> 01:34.206
God, it's hot in here.

01:34.310 --> 01:36.137
I forgot they turn the A/C off
over the weekend.

01:36.241 --> 01:38.448
Why did we even wear
suits today? Nobody's here.

01:38.551 --> 01:40.620
I guess I was sort of
on autopilot this morning.

01:40.724 --> 01:42.793
Most of the time, I'm barely
paying attention

01:42.896 --> 01:43.965
to what I'm doing.

01:44.068 --> 01:44.896
Sometimes I don't even
realize I'm at work

01:45.000 --> 01:45.965
until I'm leaving
for the day.

01:46.068 --> 01:48.068
[ Slurps ] Oh!
That coffee's from Friday.

01:48.172 --> 01:50.344
If we're gonna be trapped
here on a holiday,

01:50.448 --> 01:52.689
let's at least
be comfortable.

01:52.793 --> 01:54.655
Okay, we know basically
what they need to say.

01:54.758 --> 01:56.413
Let's just throw some stuff
out there.

01:56.517 --> 01:57.586
All right.
How about this?

01:57.689 --> 02:00.344
"Hi. I'm Kate,
and this is John,

02:00.448 --> 02:02.206
and we're responsible
for a string of murders

02:02.310 --> 02:04.344
across Central Florida
in 2003."

02:04.448 --> 02:07.517
"Hi. I'm Kate, and this is John,
and for the next few minutes,

02:07.620 --> 02:10.068
try not to imagine us
having terrifying sex."

02:10.172 --> 02:11.827
Hi. I'm Kate,
and this is John,

02:11.931 --> 02:14.206
and we flew here today
on a private fucking jet

02:14.310 --> 02:16.896
to tell you about how the
environment is in trouble.

02:17.000 --> 02:20.206
Are you giving a speech or
guiding a plane on the tarmac?

02:20.310 --> 02:21.689
I'm using my hands
to speak.

02:21.793 --> 02:23.689
Any good public speaker
will tell you

02:23.793 --> 02:26.482
that the hands are
the mouth of the torso.

02:26.586 --> 02:28.275
No one will
tell you that.

02:28.379 --> 02:31.310
But if they did,
they would use...their hands.

02:31.413 --> 02:33.482
Okay. How about this
for a second sentence?

02:33.586 --> 02:35.931
"Hampton DeVille
is going green."

02:36.034 --> 02:38.655
Ohh!
Powerful. Sorkin-esque.

02:38.758 --> 02:40.896
This is really starting
to come together.

02:41.000 --> 02:42.206
I'm hungry.

02:42.310 --> 02:43.517
Oh, are you?

02:43.620 --> 02:46.034
Yeah. I are.

02:46.137 --> 02:48.827
[ Drawers sliding ]

02:48.931 --> 02:51.034
♪♪

02:51.137 --> 02:54.000
Ooh!
Really fancy cookies.

02:54.103 --> 02:55.275
I think Grace knew
we would do this

02:55.379 --> 02:56.655
and she left those there
for us to find.

02:56.758 --> 02:59.344
I can't think of another
reason they'd be here.

02:59.448 --> 03:02.000
What else does she
have in here?

03:02.103 --> 03:03.965
-Oh, my God.
-Mmm.

03:04.068 --> 03:07.241
Is this a mouse...house?

03:09.827 --> 03:12.586
Whoa. This is crazy.

03:12.689 --> 03:14.724
The attention to detail
is shocking.

03:14.827 --> 03:16.724
Is that a coffee table
made of staples?

03:16.827 --> 03:20.241
That's Grace's portrait on
the wall above the mouse's bed.

03:20.344 --> 03:22.241
Is that a dart board
with a cat's face on it?

03:22.344 --> 03:23.482
It's clever.

03:23.586 --> 03:25.068
The floor's made
of popsicle sticks.

03:25.172 --> 03:27.275
This must have taken
hundreds of hours.

03:27.379 --> 03:30.172
It's a mouseterpiece.
Okay.

03:30.275 --> 03:31.620
You think you know someone
for years,

03:31.724 --> 03:33.413
and then you see something
like this, and you're like,

03:33.517 --> 03:35.758
"I don't know who this person
is, and I never did."

03:35.862 --> 03:38.517
I don't think I'll ever
recover from seeing this.

03:38.620 --> 03:41.551
Okay. We should really
get back to work.

03:41.655 --> 03:42.551
Definitely.

03:42.655 --> 03:45.206
[ Clanking ]

03:52.241 --> 03:55.241
Whoa.
This guy's been busy.

03:55.344 --> 03:57.551
Matt: Jackpot!

03:58.931 --> 04:02.206
[ Tchaikovsky's "Piano Concerto
No. 1 in B flat minor" playing ]

04:02.310 --> 04:10.103
♪♪

04:10.206 --> 04:17.931
♪♪

04:18.034 --> 04:25.793
♪♪

04:25.896 --> 04:33.620
♪♪

04:33.724 --> 04:42.344
♪♪

04:42.448 --> 04:44.724
Wait, Matt.
That's a Christmas tin.

04:44.827 --> 04:46.724
That popcorn
is nine months old.

04:46.827 --> 04:48.655
See? That's where
you're wrong.

04:48.758 --> 04:51.068
But don't worry.
Popcorn doesn't expire.

04:51.172 --> 04:53.344
It's like yogurt.
Oh!

04:56.344 --> 04:58.413
"I had the dream again.

04:58.517 --> 05:01.137
Christian told me
I had good taste in music.

05:01.241 --> 05:04.827
The feeling was unlike anything
else I've ever experienced.

05:04.931 --> 05:07.172
The next thing I knew,
I was flying,

05:07.275 --> 05:10.931
soaring, in fact, sitting
on Christian's shoulders,

05:11.034 --> 05:14.931
and I had no idea where
I left my bikini top."

05:17.206 --> 05:18.862
Okay.

05:18.965 --> 05:22.103
♪♪

05:22.206 --> 05:23.862
It's tasteful.

05:23.965 --> 05:26.586
♪♪

05:26.689 --> 05:30.551
Whoa. That's a lot
of stress balls.

05:30.655 --> 05:31.862
Are these bite marks?

05:31.965 --> 05:33.482
We should really
get back to work.

05:33.586 --> 05:35.931
[ Hollow clanking ]

05:38.586 --> 05:40.310
Best moment of my life

05:40.413 --> 05:44.241
was hitting a home run
in Little League.

05:44.344 --> 05:48.137
I was 9, and I was
terrible at baseball.

05:48.241 --> 05:49.655
Awful.

05:49.758 --> 05:53.965
But then, one time at bat,
I stepped up to the plate,

05:54.068 --> 05:57.586
swung as hard as I could,
and blasted it over the fence!

05:57.689 --> 06:00.413
Nobody on my team had hit
a home run all season.

06:00.517 --> 06:03.034
But there I was,
Fatty Matty,

06:03.137 --> 06:06.793
standing at home plate
stunned -- Puhh! --

06:06.896 --> 06:10.482
as the ball
flew over the fence.

06:10.586 --> 06:12.758
I have never again
felt anything

06:12.862 --> 06:16.275
even really approaching
the joy that I felt that day.

06:16.379 --> 06:19.206
Your life would be a Greek
tragedy if it weren't so boring.

06:19.310 --> 06:22.655
All right, one more pitch,
and then let's get back to work.

06:22.758 --> 06:29.275
♪♪

06:29.379 --> 06:31.241
[ Crack! ]

06:31.344 --> 06:38.137
♪♪

06:38.241 --> 06:41.344
Whoo!
Fatty Matty does it again!

06:41.448 --> 06:47.310
♪♪

06:47.413 --> 06:53.275
♪♪

06:53.379 --> 06:59.206
♪♪

06:59.310 --> 07:06.172
♪♪

07:06.275 --> 07:09.137
[ Doors creaking ]

07:09.241 --> 07:16.034
♪♪

07:16.137 --> 07:23.689
♪♪

07:23.793 --> 07:25.931
Is that...a dinosaur?

07:26.034 --> 07:27.379
[ Distant thud ]

07:27.482 --> 07:29.896
Did you hear
something?

07:30.000 --> 07:32.000
Christian: No, working from home
wasn't really an option.

07:32.103 --> 07:33.413
Too many distractions.

07:33.517 --> 07:35.310
I never should have bought
that rock tumbler.

07:35.413 --> 07:37.344
Yeah. [ Laughs ]
I don't know why I agreed

07:37.448 --> 07:39.310
to give this speech
in the first place.

07:39.413 --> 07:41.000
I mean, the last thing
I fucking need

07:41.103 --> 07:44.137
is another fucking honorary
degree from fucking Harvard.

07:44.241 --> 07:46.724
[ Laughs ] I know.

07:48.379 --> 07:50.517
All right.
Uh, talk soon, Eminem.

08:01.103 --> 08:07.517
♪♪

08:17.965 --> 08:20.517
[ Thud ]

08:20.620 --> 08:24.655
♪ I'm forever blowing bubbles

08:24.758 --> 08:28.413
♪ Pretty bubbles in the air

08:28.517 --> 08:31.517
♪ They fly so high

08:31.620 --> 08:33.896
♪ Nearly reach the sky

08:34.000 --> 08:38.827
♪ Then, like my dreams,
they fade and die ♪

08:40.482 --> 08:43.965
[ Clears throat ]
Good evening.

08:44.068 --> 08:45.931
I'm Christian DeVille.

08:46.034 --> 08:49.068
This honorary degree
from Harvard

08:49.172 --> 08:52.379
is going to sit
in the trunk of my car.

08:52.482 --> 08:55.310
Oh, come on, Chrissy.

08:55.413 --> 08:58.758
Okay.
Um, I'm Christian DeVille.

08:58.862 --> 09:01.344
And I was rejected by Harvard.

09:01.448 --> 09:03.068
But that didn't stop me

09:03.172 --> 09:05.827
from becoming
a self-important asshole.

09:10.000 --> 09:14.413
♪♪

09:14.517 --> 09:17.310
You're a wizard, Christian.

09:17.413 --> 09:20.896
So you're going to Hogwarts.

09:21.000 --> 09:23.620
[ Gasps ] Ohh!

09:24.965 --> 09:27.758
You're looking quite handsome
tonight, Professor McGonagall.

09:27.862 --> 09:30.620
Would you care to go out
for a butter beer?

09:32.862 --> 09:36.689
Shut up, Draco!
You dirty Slytherin!

09:36.793 --> 09:39.379
I'll see you
on the Quidditch field!

09:39.482 --> 09:42.482
[ Soft crunch ]

09:42.586 --> 09:44.758
Avada Kedavra, Snape!

09:46.931 --> 09:48.827
Thank you,
Mr. President of Harvard,

09:48.931 --> 09:51.965
for this honorary
doctorate degree.

09:52.068 --> 09:54.551
But it would certainly
be a shame if somebody...

09:54.655 --> 09:56.103
cut it in half!

09:56.206 --> 09:57.655
Ahh.

09:57.758 --> 09:59.482
[ Inhales sharply ]

09:59.586 --> 10:01.551
[ Sword thuds ]

10:05.413 --> 10:07.620
Hmm.

10:11.931 --> 10:15.655
♪♪

10:15.758 --> 10:18.068
Okay, Chrissy.
Here are the rules.

10:18.172 --> 10:21.655
You slice this pear,
you go back to work.

10:28.689 --> 10:31.206
[ Swish! ][ Groans ]

10:35.034 --> 10:39.827
♪♪

10:39.931 --> 10:45.344
♪♪

10:45.448 --> 10:47.379
[ Swish! ][ Groans ]

10:47.482 --> 10:53.551
♪♪

10:53.655 --> 10:56.137
[ Doors creak softly ]

10:56.241 --> 10:58.862
[ Swish! ][ Grunts ]

10:58.965 --> 11:01.000
[ Thud ]

11:04.724 --> 11:06.448
[ Crunch ]

11:06.551 --> 11:13.241
♪♪

11:13.344 --> 11:20.137
♪♪

11:20.241 --> 11:27.965
♪♪

11:28.068 --> 11:35.551
♪♪

11:35.655 --> 11:38.103
Who's out there?!

11:38.206 --> 11:42.896
♪♪

11:43.000 --> 11:45.793
-Those are my pants.
-Shit. Sorry.

11:45.896 --> 11:49.344
[ Both breathing heavily ]

11:49.448 --> 11:50.482
Can you tie my tie?

11:50.586 --> 11:51.965
It takes me like five times
every time.

11:52.068 --> 11:53.206
It'll just be faster
if you do it.

11:53.310 --> 11:54.379
Umm...

11:54.482 --> 11:57.137
-Hurry up, Jake.
-Shut up!

11:57.241 --> 12:02.310
♪♪

12:02.413 --> 12:08.034
♪♪

12:08.137 --> 12:10.689
"And, ultimately, going
green isn't just for us.

12:10.793 --> 12:13.137
Going green is for
future generations."

12:13.241 --> 12:14.965
[ Chuckles softly ]

12:15.068 --> 12:17.517
Jake:
Ohh! Mr. DeVille.

12:17.620 --> 12:19.448
Hi.

12:19.551 --> 12:21.206
What are you
doing here?

12:21.310 --> 12:23.137
Working on Labor Day,
if you can believe it.

12:23.241 --> 12:26.000
We've been holed up
in this office all day.

12:27.689 --> 12:30.206
There's an intruder
in the building.

12:30.310 --> 12:33.310
♪♪

12:33.413 --> 12:36.172
And they're still at large.

12:36.275 --> 12:38.103
Come with me.

12:40.034 --> 12:45.206
♪♪

12:45.310 --> 12:47.793
Christian: I don't think I've
ever been down here before.

12:47.896 --> 12:49.241
Matt:
This is our floor.

12:49.344 --> 12:52.482
It's sort of the nerve center
of the company.

12:52.586 --> 12:55.034
[ Fly buzzing ]

12:55.137 --> 12:57.206
It's very sad.

12:57.310 --> 13:02.413
♪♪

13:02.517 --> 13:08.206
♪♪

13:08.310 --> 13:10.758
[ Clattering ][ Christian screams ]

13:12.758 --> 13:14.793
[ Sighs ]

13:14.896 --> 13:16.827
I have to say
this little hunt

13:16.931 --> 13:20.517
is starting to feel
downright spooky.

13:20.620 --> 13:22.413
We're like
the Hardy Boys, huh?

13:22.517 --> 13:25.034
[ Chuckles ]
No. "Scooby-Doo."

13:25.137 --> 13:28.103
You're Scooby.
You're Shaggy.

13:28.206 --> 13:31.275
And I'm Velma.
She was the smart one.

13:36.379 --> 13:39.068
♪♪

13:39.172 --> 13:43.310
Matt: Well, looks like
the cafeteria's empty.

13:43.413 --> 13:46.000
Whew.

13:46.103 --> 13:48.931
Y-You know what they
used to do in "Scooby-Doo"?

13:49.034 --> 13:53.103
They'd get distracted and make
these really big sandwiches.

13:53.206 --> 13:55.172
[ Laughs ]

13:55.275 --> 13:56.655
Yeah.

13:56.758 --> 14:00.344
[ Tchaikovsky's "Piano Concerto
No. 1 in B flat minor" playing ]

14:00.448 --> 14:07.482
♪♪

14:07.586 --> 14:15.448
♪♪

14:15.551 --> 14:18.137
Christian: So you two were
the only ones here all day,

14:18.241 --> 14:19.793
and you worked
the whole time?

14:19.896 --> 14:23.034
Yeah. I guess you could say
work is our passion.

14:23.137 --> 14:26.517
Impressive. I'm a bit of
a procrastinator myself.

14:26.620 --> 14:30.172
If I don't want to do something,
oh, I just start goofing off.

14:30.275 --> 14:32.965
I can't picture that.

14:33.068 --> 14:35.448
I hate it when something
gets stuck in my teeth.

14:35.551 --> 14:36.724
Ruins my whole day.

14:36.827 --> 14:39.241
It always happens to me
with popcorn.

14:41.137 --> 14:43.413
Popped corn?

14:43.517 --> 14:45.034
Oh. Yeah.

14:45.137 --> 14:47.551
I went to the movies
last night

14:47.655 --> 14:49.862
and saw the new
Oscar-nominated

14:49.965 --> 14:53.172
animated shorts with
my friend "Popcorn" --

14:53.275 --> 14:55.310
David Corn.

14:55.413 --> 14:56.793
Anyway, the shorts were --

14:56.896 --> 14:58.965
The shorts were
really interesting shorts.

14:59.068 --> 15:02.172
-Uh, there was --
-Dave is a really solid dude.

15:03.310 --> 15:05.068
Hm.

15:05.172 --> 15:08.275
You know what I'm always tempted
to do when I'm here alone?

15:08.379 --> 15:09.620
What?

15:09.724 --> 15:11.413
Snoop around in
other people's offices.

15:11.517 --> 15:13.758
Wouldn't that be fun?

15:18.206 --> 15:21.724
"Last night I had
my favorite dream again.

15:21.827 --> 15:24.551
I was a lioness."
[ Laughs ]

15:24.655 --> 15:27.862
"Licking Christian's head.

15:27.965 --> 15:31.275
It tasted even better
than the last time."

15:31.379 --> 15:36.275
♪♪

15:36.379 --> 15:38.000
What's that?

15:38.103 --> 15:40.379
I don't know.
Let's take a look.

15:42.551 --> 15:46.724
Okay. I think I'm done looking
through John's office.

15:46.827 --> 15:50.068
♪♪

15:50.172 --> 15:52.275
Hmm.

15:59.896 --> 16:02.000
Christian: When I was
8 years old, I hit

16:02.103 --> 16:04.793
a home run in Little League,
which was a bit of a miracle

16:04.896 --> 16:06.896
because typically,
I couldn't hit a thing.

16:07.000 --> 16:09.793
[ Grunts ] Aah!

16:09.896 --> 16:12.827
All the boys used to call me
Missy Chrissy.

16:12.931 --> 16:14.724
I rode the bench all year.

16:14.827 --> 16:16.241
But final game of the season,

16:16.344 --> 16:18.517
coach had no choice
but to put me in.

16:18.620 --> 16:21.103
[ Grunts ]

16:21.206 --> 16:24.758
The game was tied.
Bottom of the ninth.

16:24.862 --> 16:26.724
I stepped up to the plate.

16:26.827 --> 16:28.758
And I knocked it
out of the park!

16:28.862 --> 16:30.448
[ Chuckles ]
You know, even though

16:30.551 --> 16:32.896
I own a multibillion-dollar
corporation...[ Spits ]

16:33.000 --> 16:35.551
...hitting that home run
is still the greatest thing

16:35.655 --> 16:37.689
that ever happened to me.

16:37.793 --> 16:40.586
[ Grunts, laughs ]

16:40.689 --> 16:42.724
Oh, G-- I'm just kidding.

16:42.827 --> 16:44.758
But those Harvard idiots
will eat that up.

16:44.862 --> 16:46.344
I'm gonna put that
in my speech.

16:46.448 --> 16:49.482
All right. One more, and
then we get back to work.

16:49.586 --> 16:53.206
Now, put a little stink
on this one, Shaggy Koufax.

16:53.310 --> 16:58.275
♪♪

16:58.379 --> 17:00.586
[ Clank! ]

17:00.689 --> 17:04.758
♪♪

17:04.862 --> 17:08.206
In your face, Shaggy!

17:08.310 --> 17:11.206
♪♪

17:11.310 --> 17:13.827
Missy Chrissy does it again!

17:13.931 --> 17:19.068
♪♪

17:19.172 --> 17:21.137
Hey, Matt!
Look what I found!

17:21.241 --> 17:24.724
Christian: And the crowd
goes wild! [ Laughs ]

17:24.827 --> 17:25.931
[ Grunts ]

17:26.034 --> 17:27.310
John! What are you
doing here?!

17:27.413 --> 17:29.172
I ordered a beautiful poster
as a little Labor Day

17:29.275 --> 17:32.137
present for my wife,
but I forgot it in my office.

17:32.241 --> 17:34.172
-What, you give Labor Day gifts?
-Well, yeah.

17:34.275 --> 17:35.379
Well, we always exchange
gifts on Labor Day.

17:35.482 --> 17:37.241
I mean, this is our first one,
but we always do it.

17:37.344 --> 17:39.827
She got me a CD tower.
John!

17:39.931 --> 17:41.344
I don't know how to
explain this to you,

17:41.448 --> 17:42.620
but Christian has been stalking
the hallways of Hampton DeVille

17:42.724 --> 17:44.310
with a sword looking for
an intruder eating popcorn,

17:44.413 --> 17:45.965
and right now
you fit the description!

17:46.068 --> 17:47.655
You need to get out of here,
or he's gonna kill you!

17:47.758 --> 17:50.310
I had a dream about this.Go!

17:50.413 --> 17:52.379
John. Ball.

17:56.310 --> 17:57.931
Who were you
just talking to?

17:58.034 --> 18:01.000
Nobody. I mean, myself.

18:02.482 --> 18:06.655
You wouldn't lie to me,
would you, Shaggy?

18:06.758 --> 18:08.517
[ Crunch ]

